#--: Ownership rules

Rules for 'objects':

#ul:
  [#*: all objects have a single owner or parent which cannot be itself]
  [#*: ownership is to direct children only, it does not extend to grandchildren and
    there is no direct access to grandchildren]
  [#*: valtypes are copy by value. Each can only have a single owner, but easily
    copied so can make a new copy with a new owner.]
  [#*: reftypes are copy by reference. Can only have a single owner, but can be
    loaned via function calls or given away to a function call via a 'take'
    param]
  [#*: objects can only be disposed by their owner and no self-ownership so objects
    cannot dispose of themselves]
  [#*: all reftypes in object fields must be initialised and cannot be removed, only
    swapped]
  [#*: and, methods on reftype fields cannot be passed anything that is not owned
    (no borrowed references, eg self to prevent killing ourselves) Why not other
    borrowed references besides self?]
  [#*: ...so, reftypes in calls can only be borrowed (from parent call) or owned
    directly (local var). this.reftype???]
  [#*: returned reftypes always give ownership from function to caller. 'take' 
    arguments give ownership from caller to function (and are no longer valid at
    the caller from that point forward)]
  [#*: initialisation? The one true constructor must be called supplying all values,
    although default values can be used for valtypes.]
  [#*: destructor? There is a default destructor to recursively free all reftypes.
    Can be overridden to free/cleanup non-memory resources. Can return a single
    reftype from the class. How would that look?]

#--: IDEA: Pointers, ownership, give/take on valtypes

#ul:
  [#*: 'this' is always passed as a pointer. object cannot be destroyed within a
    method, so should be safe even for reftypes]
  [#*: more efficient for large reftypes - records. 'this' implies this
    particular instance so signals that pass by reference is not used]
  [#*: can never assign to 'this']
  [#*: can valtypes be passed by 'take'? Yes. But note that this would destroy the
    var in the caller. Would need to return this value if you want to pass it
    back. Compiler would need to be smart enough to pass a pointer back on return
    to avoid copy both ways. Would be more efficient for large records.]

