  [#*: calling a 'type' (object definition) in a runtime expression is the same as
    #~"mytype.create" (with arguments, if any). There can be other constructors
    with different names but they must be called explicitly (eg.
    #~"mytype.create2"). This also applies to #~"meta.create" = #~"meta" and also
    #~"_" (underscore) can be used as #~"_.create". Only for normal
    expressions, this does NOT happen for generic parameters.]
  [#*: 'callable' instances. If *all* apply such that:
    #ul:
      [#*: a #~"term" as accessed as the callable within call syntax (ie. with a named
      argument (#~"call_labelled"); or a single unnamed argument (#~"term binop" in an
      #~"operation") or with no argument (#~"term" *only* in a #~"binop")]
      [#*: that is *not* in an binop with an operator and argument (#~"term id term")]
      [#*: that is in a non-constant context (eg. not in a #~"data" clause)]
      [#*: that term refers to an instance with a #~"call" method

        #p:
        Then, the #~"call" method will be implicitly called on that instance. Note that
        this makes referring to the instance itself more complicated. To refer to the
        instance itself, an ownership specifier must be used (eg. #~"myinstance.take" or
        #~".borrow" or #~".lock"). For this reason, creating a #~"call" method on an object
        should be carefully considered. Note that simple #~"for" sugar (see below) over
        an interable instance *requires* the default iterator to return a callable
        instance (with no arguments) as described here.

        ]
      ]
  [#*: binding to an instance in a #~"for" where that instance has an #~"iterate" method
    that returns an iterator that takes no argument, is equivalent to calling
    that #~"iterate" method before any iteration has begun and then using that
    returned iterator before each iteration. eg. #~"for i: myiterable" is
    equivalent to #~"with _x: myiterable.iterate for i: _x" (#~"_x" is an example
    only and will actually be a compiler generated reference that is not
    otherwise accessible)]
  [#*: (this is not really sugar but compiler added attributes. see also #~"take",
    #~"borrow", #~"lock", #~"limit", #~"generic"). Item definitions implicitly have
    'public' and 'private' as members that expose the public interface (as
    defined with the #~"as" keyword) and the private interface (all methods/fields
    of an item). 'private' is only accessable from within the item definition,
    although external 'friend' methods and items can declare that they support
    'item.private' and methods of the orginal item can call/instantiate those
    functions/items. If those friend methods/items return a borrowed item, then
    the original item is locked... iterators can be implimented this way]
  [#*: Generators with #~"yield" is the largest 'sugar'. It creates an entire compiler
    generated class/record to turn the yielding function 'inside out']

