Compile time numeric contants are a separate series of types based on the
smallest number of bits (rounded up to nearest power of 2 that is >= 8) that
can hold them. Each type has different methods for 'call' which determines
their default runtime type, and other conversion methods provided this constant
can losslessly be converted to those types. Some rules:

#ul:
  [#*: default numeric type is i64 for all integer constants that can be stored in
    an i64. Larger numbers have no 'call' method and must be explicitly converted
    to a runtime type.]
  [#*: default numeric type is f64 for all float constants that can be stored in an
    f64. Larger numbers have no 'call' method and must be explicitly converted to
    a runtime type.]
  [#*: negative constants have no 'u' methods (eg 'u64') since negative numbers
    cannot be converted to an unsigned type]

The constant types:

#ul:
  [#*: #~"cip8" - constant positive int that can fit in 8 bits (supported methods: u8
    u16 i16 u32 i32 u64 i64 u128 i128 c8 c32) - note, not i8 because it may not
    fit. Default (retult of 'call') is i64.]
  [#*: #~"cin8" - constant negative int that can fit in 8 bits (supported methods: i8
    i16 i32 i64 i128). Default (retult of 'call') is i64.]
  [#*: #~"cip16" - supports methods as for #~"cip8" but NOT u8, i8, c8]
  [#*: #~"cin16" - supports methods as for #~"cin8" but NOT i8]
  [#*: #~"cip32"]
  [#*: #~"cin32"]
  [#*: #~"cip64"]
  [#*: #~"cin64"]
  [#*: #~"cip128" - no default (result of call method)]
  [#*: #~"cin128" - no default (result of call method)]
  [#*: #~"cf16" - constant float that can fit in a f16]
  [#*: #~"cf32" - constant float that can fit in a f32]
  [#*: #~"cf64" - constant float that can fit in a f64]
  [#*: #~"cf128" - constant float that can fit in a f128]
  [#*: #~"cc8" - constant character that can fit in 8 bits, always positive (supported
    methods: u8 u16 i16 u32 i32 u64 i64 u128 i128 c8 c32) - note, not i8 because
