#---: Ownership:

  - immutable - top level (unit level) immutable type. The names of top level
    items are constant, cannot be redefined. Functions, #~"data", numeric types
    (although, these are passed by value so not a limitation that they are
    immutable)
  - free - (anonymous). Ownership is free to convey to the LHS/receiver. eg.
    return values from functions (not from iterators though); or all valtypes.
    An owned reftype variable can be converted to a free variable by using the
    #~"take" predefined type the the variable as the parameter. If ownership of a
    reftype is not taken by the LHS, the variable will be destroyed after the
    current statementline.
  - owned - var created locally or a "taken" parameter in a function body
  - borrowed - reftypes passed in via standard (non- #~"take") function parameter
  - linked - dotted member object of a composite type (eg record/class)

Valtypes are always 'free' because they are always copied to new locations.

'linked' are dotted members of another parent variable (as with all vars, the
parent also is owned, borrowed or linked). This is a special class of ownership
(eg dotted members are not automatically owned just because you own the parent)
and have some additional restrictions (ie. they must be replaced if changed).

Items returned from a function calls are always free.

immutable - yes/no (if yes, cannot be assigned to) - top level item usually

writeable - yes/no (if yes, can be assigned to) Could be no, but not immutable
eg an expression with no name

free - (anonymous) - yes/no (if yes, can be assigned from)



#---: Lock type:

All vars have a lock type. Unused local vars and parameters start with 'none'.

(For arguments at call sites; also 'cast', 'case', 'for' can lock target
object)

  - blocked - target of #~"case" (if not #~"take" -en), named (private members
    too?); local var definitions (including 'casts', eg. #~"newvar: object.protocol") 
    that take a non-'free' var on the RHS will take a lock while in scope. 
  - exclusive - a reftype directly passed into a call by name, or receiver in a
    method call
  - shared - a parent of a linked reftype passed into a call
  - none - for the 'free' ownership types: valtypes, result of function calls,
    unused local vars/arguments (?? what is that?)

'blocked' makes the target totally unreferencable by that name. 

'exclusive' can have methods called on it but no reuse elsewhere and no child
access. All methods must take an exclusive lock on the receiver immediately
before the call.

'shared' will be for all parent items in a dotted chain except the last (which
will have an exclusive lock if it is a reftype field being passed); EXCEPT if
the final item is a valtype (in which case, there are no shared locks on the
parent items or the valtype)

'none' is essentially a noop for completeness; these situations have lock type
of 'none':

  - 'free' ownership types
  - as yet unreferenced vars
  - the results of function calls (they are 'free')
  - unit level items (because they are immutable (?)) - incl. functions, and
    unit level constant numbers and 'data'.
  - valtypes (they are free)... this includes the entire "path" up to that
    valtype - ie. no shared locks on parent components of a valtype reference

The typesystem will check the locking of the parts of all calls. Multiple
shared locks on an object are ok, but only one exclusive lock on an object is
permitted. This includes the call (method) itself, which will need an exclusive
lock on the parent (if any).

After a call, all related locks are popped and cleared and the resulting object
is 'none'/'free' (except for iterators).

All locks take a reference to the location where the lock was taken for error
reporting purposes.

