#--: Ownership v3

#---: Attributes: type, ownership, mutability, lock

#----: Type

Type is an attribute of the object (not of the name).

- definition type (deftype) - top level object definition (record, class, enum,
  functions/methods, numeric constants, etc.) Compiler metadata only and are
  immutable.
- reference type (reftype) - has a runtime 'pointer'/'reference' to a type of
  possibly indeterminate size, has identity etc. Can only be created in
  run-time code.
- value type (valtype) - an inline block of data with a fixed size for this
  type. Has value semantics. Can be sources from some top level definitions
  (compile time numeric constants, function 'references'). Can only be created
  in run-time code.

#----: Ownership

Ownership is an attribute related to each expression in a function body.

- free: no name (anonymous); result of a standard call (except from a
  'borrowed' return as from an iterator); result of 'take' call; all valtypes
  are essentially 'free' to copy.
- owned: local owned var; #~"taken" reftype parameter
- borrowed: local borrowed var; non- #~"taken" reftype parameter; 'borrowed'
  return type of a function; result from an iterator; 'this' is always borrowed
- linked: child reftype field of an object 

linked....for returning borrowed, must be linked or borrowed (cannot be
  owned because it wont exist afterwards)

#----: Locality

Attribute related to the location of the object:

* local - local variable in the current function scope. Variable will be
  destroyed when that scope ends. Includes:
  ** free (anonymous) objects
  ** Local variables (owned variables; and shared variables that are bound to
    owned local vars) 
  ** 'taken' function parameters 
  ** (others?)
* non-local - variable sourced from outside the current function scope that
  will live on after the function returns. Includes:
  ** non- 'taken' parameters (shared parameters)
  ** linked variables; and shared vars bound to linked variables
  ** (others?)

Locality is passed in from the source. 'taken' variables become local but
otherwise a shared var will have the same locality as its source.



#----: Mutability

Mutability is an attribute related to the name of a 'variable'. The variable
value may still be mutable.

- immutable - top level definitions; method names of object; 'this' inside an
  object
- mutable - name can be copied to (with a compatible RHS, previous reftype
  value will be destroyed, valtypes will be copied over); or swapped

#----: Lock

Lock type is an attribute related to each expression part in a function body.
Expressions 'hold' locks over other variable names/values. Only for reftypes;
valtypes and deftype always have a lock type of 'none'. When an expression is
assigned to a name, the expression locks are then carried with that name and
released when the name falls out of scope.

It is an error to attempt to take a lock that breaks the below rules:

- exclusive - holder can do anything (call method, 'take' etc). No other
  expression can do anything with this expression while the lock is held. (ie.
  method calls, use as argument, reference children). No other lock of any type
  can be taken. Expression type must have a locktype of 'none' before an
  exclusive lock can be taken.
- shared - can reference children, cannot call methods, cannot take an
  exclusive lock. Expression type must have a locktype of 'none' or other
  'shared' locks only before taking a shared lock.
- none - no restrictions, can take a shared or exclusive lock. Top level
  definitions always have lock type of 'none' and take no locks on their RHS.
  Top level definitions are immutable and shareable - they are always deftypes
  or valtypes.

#---: Operations

#----: createval

Create a new valtype variable. LHS must be a new label. RHS must be a valtype,
LHS becomes a copy of that value type.

#----: createref

Create a new reftype variable. LHS must be a new label. New variable will hold
all the locks that the RHS has taken.

RHS:

- must be a reftype
- RHS parents and 'leaf' must have lock type of 'none', else error
- if free (use 'take' if required), LHS owns that expression. No locks.
- if owned or borrowed, LHS borrows that expression and is given an exclusive
  lock to the RHS leaf and shared locks to all RHS parents until end of LHS's
  scope (the locks are transferred to the LHS name)

#----: copyval

Only for valtypes. LHS must be owned (valtypes can never be borrowed or
linked). LHS name must be 'mutable'.

RHS must be assignable to the type of the LHS type (same type or losslessly
convertable to a larger numeric type in all cases).

#----: moveref

Only for reftypes. LHS must be owned or linked.

- RHS must be assignable to the LHS (the same type?)
- RHS must be free or owned. Owned will be automatically promoted to free
- if RHS is owned, its name will be destroyed after move
- LHS prior value will be destroyed after move

#----: swapref

Only for reftypes. Both LHS and RHS must be:

- same type (exactly)
- mutable variable names
- owned (not borrowed)
- must be able to take an exclusive lock on both immediately before the swap

#----: call (change this to 'locking'? Happens in all expressions)

A series of locking steps are done around a call.

- new lock frame added (?)
- arguments processed left to right recursively (may involve a sub call)
- shared lock taken on each parent
- exclusive lock taken on each 'leaf' (final part of path)
- 'loaned' returns ???


#----: take

- convert a 'mutable' name to a 'free' (unnamed) variable
- variable must be 'owned'
- can only 'take' local undotted variable names (no field member names)
- the previous name is no longer available after the 'take'

#----: usage?

- iterators - return loaned items
- 'object.myprotocol' - returns a loaned item? Exclusively locks parent object.
  This item can be created on the stack since it will not outlive the current
  scope; no allocation is required.
- 'myprotocol from: take object' - returns a new owned item. Can never get
  back to enclosed item

#--: More thoughts on ownership/locking

For function returns:

- take - (default) returns an owned object. Arguments are locked during the
  call but released when the object is returned. Caller is responsible for
  destroying returned object (this will happen when it falls out of scope)
- borrow - returns a borrowed object. Arguments are locked during the call and
  remain in place until the returned object falls out of scope. Caller is NOT
  responsible for destroying returned object (it lives inside the associated
  object) A borrow return REQUIRES a lock on the parameter where the returned
  value lives
- lock - N/A

For parameters:

- take - will take an exclusively owned object. It will no longer be valid in
  the caller
- borrow - (default) will borrow the object. Cannot store or return it. Can
  only call methods on it
- lock - will borrow the object, LOCKING it in the caller even after the call
  returns (lock is bound to the life of the returned object). Can store (in a
  new object only...) or return it. Can only call methods on it

Inline (code):

- take - will take an exclusively owned object. Target (if a named address)
  will no longer be valid going forward
- borrow - (default) will borrow the object. Will lock the target
- lock - same as borrow.

In arguments:

same as 'Inline'. The specifier is optional and can be included to be
explicit/readable. But if the specifier is missing, the ownership type
specified in the function definition will still apply which may affect
availability of a named var after the call (for lock and take)

It is an error to explicitly provide an incompatible ownership/locking type.
eg. borrow arg, when the param is #~"take". Can this happen? if you #~"take arg" at
the call site for a locked arg, then the call site must keep a lock on the
anonymous var until the end of scope.


